Customizing a ggplot theme

The display of everything on your map that isnt data can is controlled by the theme. You have a lot of flexibility here. Im just going to demonstrate a few things to get you started.

Required packages

This example uses the following packages:

library(tidyverse)

Sample data

I have a dataframe called countries with national boundaries in Africa. I can use ggplot() and geom_sf() to make a quick chloropleth map with variations in color to represent the estimated GDP. Here is a map using theme_void() as a starting point.

gdp_map <- ggplot(countries) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = gdp_md_est)) +
  ggtitle(label = "Sample map of Africa",
          subtitle = "Variation in GDP") +
  theme_void()

gdp_map

This doesnt look too bad, and all of the edits I make below will make it much, much worse. But there may be a situation in which knowing how to make one or more of these edits will allow you to improve a map.

Plot background

I can set the color and outline for the plot background.

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = "gray",
                                       linetype = "dashed"))

Panel background

The panel background is the rectangle around your data (not including titles and legends), and you can customize it the same way.

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"))

Plot margins

You can also set the margins around the outside of the plot with plot.margin. t is for top, r is for right, b is for bottom, and l is for left.

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"),
        plot.margin = margin(t = 10, r = 10, b = 10, l = 10, unit = "pt"))

Legend

You can place the legend to the right, left, top, or bottom of the map.

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"),
        plot.margin = margin(t = 10, 
                             r = 10, 
                             b = 10, 
                             l = 10, unit = "pt"),
        legend.position = "bottom")

You can leave the legend off by setting legend.position = "none".

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"),
        plot.margin = margin(t = 10, 
                             r = 10, 
                             b = 10, 
                             l = 10, unit = "pt"),
        legend.position = "none")

Or you can place it over the map by specifying coordinates (relative to the map panel). Placing it at c(0.5, 0.5) will place it right in the middle of your map (which you probably dont want).

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"),
        plot.margin = margin(t = 10, 
                             r = 10, 
                             b = 10, 
                             l = 10, unit = "pt"),
        legend.position = c(0.5, 0.5))

Heres a better placement.

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"),
        plot.margin = margin(t = 10, 
                             r = 10, 
                             b = 10, 
                             l = 10, unit = "pt"),
        legend.position = c(0.2, 0.25))

You can also specify the legend background:

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"),
        plot.margin = margin(t = 10, 
                             r = 10, 
                             b = 10, 
                             l = 10, unit = "pt"),
        legend.position = c(0.2, 0.25),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "yellow",
                                         color = NA))

The legend.margin parameter works the same way as plot.margin.

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"),
        plot.margin = margin(t = 10, 
                             r = 10, 
                             b = 10, 
                             l = 10, unit = "pt"),
        legend.position = c(0.2, 0.25),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "yellow",
                                         color = NA),
        legend.margin = margin(t = 6, 
                             r = 6, 
                             b = 6, 
                             l = 6, unit = "pt"))

Axes

The theme_void() theme we used as a starting point has no axis text, but you can add it back in.

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"),
        plot.margin = margin(t = 10, 
                             r = 10, 
                             b = 10, 
                             l = 10, unit = "pt"),
        legend.position = c(0.2, 0.25),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "yellow",
                                         color = NA),
        legend.margin = margin(t = 6, 
                             r = 6, 
                             b = 6, 
                             l = 6, unit = "pt"),
        axis.text = element_text())

Gridlines

And you can also customize grid lines

gdp_map +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk",
                                       color = NA),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cadetblue",
                                        color = "gray",
                                        linetype = "dotted"),
        plot.margin = margin(t = 10, 
                             r = 10, 
                             b = 10, 
                             l = 10, unit = "pt"),
        legend.position = c(0.2, 0.25),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "yellow",
                                         color = NA),
        legend.margin = margin(t = 6, 
                             r = 6, 
                             b = 6, 
                             l = 6, unit = "pt"),
        axis.text = element_text(),
        panel.grid = element_line(color = "pink",
                                  linetype = "dotted"))
